  <div class="nav-spacer"></div>
  <div  id="rootContainer" class="root-container">
<div  id="content">
	<div  class="article-feature-image-full-width-container --slim" data-background="https://granta.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ezeano-feature-image-2.jpg" style="background-image: url(https://granta.com/wp-content/uploads/2025/09/ezeano-feature-image-2.jpg)"></div>	<div  class="background-grey --no-padding background-gradient background-box-shadow">
		<div class="excerpt-article__wrapper article-main__container">
			<div class="container-fluid">
				<div class="row">
					<div class="col-lg-8 article-content">
						<div class="article-twenty-twenty-style-title-meta">
    <h1 id="main-heading" class="article-feature-image-standard_meta article-twenty-twenty-style-title"> Trying Times</h1>
            <h3 class=" article-twenty-twenty-style-contributor"> <a class="contributor-link" href="https://granta.com/contributor/adachioma-ezeano/">Adachioma Ezeano</a></h3>
            
</div>						<div class="d-lg-none">
							   <div class="d-block d-md-none d-lg-block mb-4 ">
                  <!-- sidebar advert -->
           <!-- <div class="hidden-xs hidden-sm hidden-md">
                <div class="article-sidebar__right__advert">
					it exists                </div>
            </div> -->

           <!-- 1st custom text widget used for ads-->
       <div class="widget__article-sidebar-text"><iframe title="litbreakerAdvert" width="300" height="250" scrolling=No frameborder=0 marginheight=0 marginwidth=0 src="https://litbreaker.nui.media/pipeline/519067/0/vh?z=litbreaker&dim=514841&kw=&click="><script type="text/javascript" language="JavaScript" src="https://litbreaker.nui.media/pipeline/519067/0/vj?z=litbreaker&dim=514841&kw=&click=&abr=$scriptiniframe"></script><noscript><a href="https://litbreaker.nui.media/pipeline/519067/0/cc?z=litbreaker" aria-label="See more information about this advert"><img decoding="async" src="https://litbreaker.nui.media/pipeline/519067/0/vc?z=litbreaker&dim=514841&kw=&click=&abr=$imginiframe" width="300" height="250" alt="" border="0"></a></noscript></iframe></div>   </div>						</div>
						<div class='article-twenty-twenty-style-content mb-5 '><p>The airport smelled of burning when Iruka Akintola arrived, but as she stepped off the airstair she saw no source for it. Her phone rang, a steady hum that she ignored. A thinnish woman with a small frame, Iruka chucked her scarf around her neck and bent into her armoured SUV, one of six in a convoy.</p>
<p>‘Okay,’ she said, and the driver pulled away.</p>
<p>Slowly, the car dipped into the potholes that covered the sandy brown roads. Outside, children lined the roadside begging for alms. Iruka watched them with a detached effort. Amid the heat, the traffic, the noise of motorcycles, and the endless phone calls, Iruka chose to watch the children, focusing on a slender girl with a long neck. The girl looked like a horse, Iruka thought. She also looked, vaguely, like Uchenna, her other daughter.</p>
<p>Iruka was headed home. Or more precisely, to her second husband’s home, the colonial-style mansion with the green turrets where he had grown up. Usually, she didn’t care for such architecture, but she loved him, and had, over time, come to love all he loved, idolize all he adored, including Uchenna. Especially Uchenna. That needy child who from birth cried without cease. As a teen facing menarche, Uchenna threatened to lock herself in her room until Iruka returned from a summit in Oslo. But Iruka was never going to abandon Oslo. So her new husband stepped in, phoning Iruka to detail how he managed it, how he supervised Uchenna as she bathed because she insisted. The news gave Iruka a small heart attack, guilt gnawing at her for minutes. But she named it nothing, choosing instead to love this man who had become a father to her daughters and, surprisingly, to love Uchenna even more, with all her excess needs.</p>
<p>Her phone kept vibrating, a stubborn buzz she ignored.</p>
<p>‘Madam, are you there?’ The driver asked.</p>
<p>‘Where else will I be, Erastus?’ Her tone was soft. She wanted to sound hopeful. Hope: the belief that a stable tomorrow would come if today were lived with measured calmness. She was a woman committed to good manners and rigid routines. Nothing vexed her more than dramatics or hysterics – such things belonged in the cinema.</p>
<p>Erasmus, with the convoy, passed sleek cars and rickety ones, stone pillars, the manicured gardens of Goshen Estate, and the towering All Saints Anglican Cathedral. They curved off a road fringed with trimmed shrubs, then onto a long street with a cobblestone path, the car jerking over bumps.</p>
<p>Less than half an hour later, Erasmus cruised into the driveway of the white house. Iruka looked up at the turrets, and the sight filled her with anger rather than relief. Nothing had changed. Except for the net stretched across the tennis court, now caked in red dust, everything else was just as she’d left it five months ago.</p>
<p>‘Don’t drive in yet.”</p>
<p>‘Madam?’ Erasmus sounded surprised.</p>
<p>‘Drive around more. Thanks.’</p>
<p>Erasmus reversed, and then asked, ‘Sorry Madam but – to where?’</p>
<p>Iruka did not answer. In her thirties, she had expected life to reveal its masterplan. But here she was at sixty-one still groping in the dark, dodging calls from her daughters and seeking comfort from her driver, a man with insufficient expectations, a man with no expectation beyond the day ahead.</p>
<p>‘Madam, you really do not want me to go in?’</p>
<p>‘This man,’ Iruka sighed. ‘Erastus, please do not choose today to be dumb. Drive around a bit more is the instruction. Obey! Thanks.’ Irrespective of how she felt, Iruka felt that she should say the necessary words with measured exactness.</p>
<p>‘Yes, Madam. My apologies.’ Erasmus bowed his head, then signaled the rest of the convoy over the radio before taking a different road. They passed a secondary school – one of those elegant ones named after a British figure.</p>
<p>Besides her roofing and furniture businesses, Iruka owned six schools: two in Abuja, three in Port Harcourt, and one (the most prestigious) in Lagos. She had named them all after her second husband: Sir Gozie Academy. She knew the name lacked elegance. She didn’t love it – but she loved the man. Gozie was her true love, for making her feel raptured, for making her tingle with desire. He stirred her from the verges of herself and made her like herself more.</p>
<p>As they passed a children’s hospital that backed onto an orphanage, Iruka looked away, away too from the Madonna and Child statues opposite, as if something in the whiteness of those buildings might judge her. Near Main Market, she asked the driver if there were fresh red tomatoes at home.</p>
<p>He hesitated. ‘Yes, Madam. I mean, I am sure the chef can arrange for tomatoes if there are none at home, Madam.’</p>
<p>‘Do you mind if I get down to buy tomatoes?’ she asked. Erasmus glanced at her. ‘Do I mind if –’ He glanced back at the road. ‘I do not mind. But Madam, are you sure it is a good idea?’</p>
<p>‘What is a better idea, Erastus?’</p>
<p>‘<em>Erasmus</em>, Madam.’</p>
<p>‘Ah, my memory fails me sometimes. But you must forgive my errors, just as you must allow yourself some.’</p>
<p>‘Okay, Madam. But I – I do not know the right thing to do. I am wondering, Madam, if maybe I can phone the chef and ask?’ He stammered.</p>
<p>Iruka chuckled. ‘Never mind.’</p>
<p>She had always known the right thing to do. She had weathered major upheavels in her life, including her first marriage, the death of her first husband, Mark, and then her marriage to Gozie. Iruka always knew how to act, planning carefully so that shock never took over.</p>
<p>As a good investor, she could compare patterns and connect links that others might overlook. And now, in the matter with her daughters, she was applying the same skills she brought to her investments. It wasn’t as though she hadn’t suffered while coming to terms with what she was about to do. She had. This journey was a kind of suffering in itself; her return was her torment.</p>
<p>Near Goshen Estate, the convoy slowed, for the road was crowded with schoolchildren. Cars honked, then settled into a queue behind them.</p>
<p>‘Please, be careful,’ she said.</p>
<p>‘Yes, Madam,’ the driver said.</p>
<p>Iruka’s gaze rested on a group of boys teasing a cluster of girls – teenage antics, careless and loud. The boys were neatly dressed, their belt buckles glinting in the sun. A few had small plastic combs tucked into their hair. The girls, fresh-faced and laughing, flaunted powdered faces and pink lips, their braids gathered neatly into buns, colourful pullovers stylishy draped around their necks.</p>
<p>‘Children,’ she said, with disapproval. ‘To them, everything is just black and white, everything. They think they know it all. How many do you have, Erastus?’</p>
<p>‘Just two boys, Madam.’</p>
<p>‘Well, aren’t you lucky there?’</p>
<p>‘We thank God, Madam.’</p>
<p>‘Two boys,’ Iruka said. ‘Boys are better.’</p>
<p>As a teenager, Iruka had been left alone by boys. She grew up in a rural village, where everyday things – Blue Band Butter, for instance – tasted different. Water’s taste, a rusty tang. Chickens and goats outnumbered cars, and survival meant forgetting luxuries as well as the murk of one’s miseries. Whatever life offered was called beautiful and no one complained. Iruka absorbed it, but Iruka also labored to escape it. After university, where she studied accounting, Iruka began her career as a compliance analyst at Apex Bank Nigeria, before joining Mark Akintola Nigeria Ltd, a furniture company, as their showroom manager. A year later, she married Mark Akintola, a self-sufficient man she loved for being like her, so aligned in restraint. The marriage was blessed with twin girls: Uchenna and Urenna. After Mark’s death in a plane crash – a tragedy reported in the national news – Iruka followed Gozie’s advice. Gozie, her late husband’s banker and dear childhood friend, had suggested that she trade Mark’s assets: his properties, investments, and companies.</p>
<p>Iruka did so. She invested in the stock market, established and expanded her corporation: furniture manufacturing, roofing, schools, and more. Soon she became a board member of various global initiatives and the first female Chairman of Apex Bank Nigeria. Iruka Akintola knew her aura, her capabilities, her appetites. She was in control of herself, acutely self-aware. Yet despite this – the plaques and shields in her trophy room, the public acclaim – Iruka felt betrayed by her own natural flaws. It troubled her that, despite the promises of costly creams, diets, surgeries, and treatments, ageing had chosen cruelty: carving deep, relentless lines into her skin, hollowing pits underneath her eyes, amplifying her years with merciless precision.</p>
<p>‘When you drive my husband,’ Iruka asked, ‘do you go through this street?’ She wished she hadn’t.</p>
<p>‘Yes Madam, this is the only route out of –’</p>
<p>‘At this time? When these girls . . . when these kids get out of school?’</p>
<p>‘Um.’</p>
<p>‘Erasmus?’</p>
<p>‘I know, Madam . . . I’m trying to think . . . Oga concludes his work at 4 p.m., Madam.’</p>
<p>‘And he insists on going home at 4?’</p>
<p>‘He does, Madam. Oga is good with time.’</p>
<p>‘I am not asking what my husband is good with, Erasmus. I am asking if he –’</p>
<p>‘It does not take long to drive through the girls –’</p>
<p>‘Please do not interrupt me, Erasmus. And I said kids, not girls. Why do you keep saying girls?’</p>
<p>‘Sorry Madam . . . I think I said kids as well, but I’m sorry if that wasn’t the correct thing to say.’</p>
<p>‘While with me, Erasmus, please never use contractions,’ she murmured, as though speaking to herself. But the driver heard her, and he immediately apologized for saying ‘I’m’ instead of ‘I am.’</p>
<p>Iruka was going through trying times. Trying times – that was what they were. As though time itself was trying her, grinding down her withered patience. Iruka, who willed everything about herself to remain a mystery to others. Iruka, who rarely spoke during car rides. Aside from Anglican hymns, which she allowed the drivers to play only if she knew the lyrics and melody, Iruka loathed music. Digressions and interruptions not initiated by her startled her; choruses and refrains not led by her drained her. Anything unfamiliar to Iruka simply did not exist. She was a planner.</p>
<p>Beauty, Iruka’s mother, had been sick for three years before dying from a nervous breakdown. During that time, Iruka sent Uchenna and Urenna, along with three nurses, to her mother’s home and visited eight times. Still, Beauty grumbled that, aside from administering medication, the nurses were indifferent to her needs, too apathetic to properly care. What she wanted was her daughter. But Iruka, preoccupied with Apex Bank duties, told Beauty to sheathe her weakness and not pester her with visitation demands. To further prove her love though, she built a mansion for Beauty on the very land where the woman was later laid to rest. Iruka mourned her. But she also wished people would appreciate how austere decisions kept the show on the road. The world celebrated her achievements, but how had her own family shown their gratitude? When would they learn that she wasn’t a wild lion but a woman desiring and needing familial love?</p>
<p>Years ago, when her biographer, a <em>New York Times </em>journalist, requested a tour of her various properties, including the New York penthouse, houses in Maryland and D.C., and several in Europe, Iruka responded by emailing photos of the properties to keep the woman away. It was not an easy book to read, that biography. The fictions the woman had invented carried defeatist tangs, but they were a good distraction from the lean, believable truth that Uchenna offered during her interview. Uchenna had said, and the biographer had written: ‘Iruka is a cold mother, militaristic, blue. An uninteresting, self-centered lady full of particular angsts. A dull sleep is livelier.’</p>
<p>That year, during the Christmas holiday, half in Enugu and the rest in London, both girls maintained a reasonable distance. And though it was a Saturday when Iruka read the biography, the only time of the week that permitted their fifteen minutes of sex, Iruka locked herself in her room and ignored Gozie when he knocked asking if he was needed. At dinner, everyone in the family wore white and posed for pictures. Uchenna stood beside Urenna, but never near her mother or her stepfather. The moments they shared during that trip were the compulsory ones: breakfast at 9 a.m, dinner at 6 p.m.</p>
<p>‘What else do you expect from teenagers?’ Gozie asked, trying to comfort Iruka.</p>
<p>‘To love their mother? Is that no longer an option?’</p>
<p>‘Well, they are teens . . .’</p>
<p>‘And teen commandments say, “Thou shalt loathe thy mother?” Gospeller Gozie, you tell me,’ Iruka said, carefully avoiding the word <em>hate</em>, for she feared some things once spoken aloud willed themselves into being. Gozie delayed as though giving his next words more thought. ‘Babe, no. Teenagers will always prefer friends to mothers. You know that. Calm down, okay? They will be alright.’ At the end of the holiday, Gozie usually dropped the girls off at school, but Iruka insisted on doing it herself. Her convoy of Cadillacs lined the school gate as she climbed out, saying, ‘Hug Mom, girls. Now.’</p>
<p>Both girls rushed into her, and Iruka pulled them into a tight embrace, holding them longer than usual. She didn’t let go, not even after noticing Uchenna watching another woman with her two girls. The woman, a playful giggler, plucked hibiscus flowers and tucked them into her daughters’ hair before rushing to her car, shouting, ‘Chase me or love me, good for me – Bye, angels!’ Iruka squeezed tighter, as if to drown out the childish noise of the other woman.</p>
<p>Uchenna said, ‘Mom, stop. Please. You’re hurting me.’</p>
<p>Iruka stopped, then, inspired by fear: ‘Your steps will be directed by God. You will aways remember who you are. Your father, wherever he is, will be proud. You will never be deceived by enemies into doubting that your mother never sat to watch your infant heads.’</p>
<p>Urenna uttered a soft <em>Amen</em>, before pulling away with her boxes. She pecked her mother a tiny, misty kiss that made Iruka smile. And right there, Iruka made a resolution to become a more affectionate mother.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">–</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>That was almost eighteen years ago, a time when everything was still sturdy enough to hold their family dinners. Things were different. Last Thanksgiving dinner, as Gozie and Iruka kissed before the girls, as Iruka blessed the meals, repeating, <em>thank you Sweet Lord, for ours is a perfect family</em>, Uchenna quietly pushed out her chair and left the table.</p>
<p>Iruka, that night, heard the girls arguing, but, as was usual for her, she drifted off to sleep, letting them be adults – never intervening, never bothering, not even with probing pities.</p>
<p>Later, after Uchenna had left the house, Iruka walked down to the cinema and turned off the screen; a black-and-white documentary was flickering, and no one was watching it. She stepped into Uchenna’s room, which lay between the cinema and the game room, then walked out and entered Urenna’s, where she asked first if they were alright, and then:</p>
<p>‘Why did Uchenna leave so early?’</p>
<p>‘Mom, please, ask Uchenna.’</p>
<p>‘I just checked her room. It’s empty. Did you say something you shouldn’t have?’ Iruka asked. Urenna stood up from the bed, grabbed her phone, and left her mother standing alone in the room.</p>
<p>At 3 p.m. the next day, Uchenna called her mother. And for close to an hour, she cried, uttering words that condemned Gozie, words so scathing that Iruka cringed. Their FaceTime call stretched longer than anything they had shared. Iruka, giving all her attention to her daughter, wished she had been a cautious mother. Uchenna’s voice was unsteady, full of sniffs and stumbles, silences filled with whimpers and a desperate need to breathe:</p>
<p>‘Mom, I can’t hold it in anymore.’</p>
<p>‘Mom?’</p>
<p>‘Uchenna?’ was all Iruka could say. Her voice was seized by grim disappointment, which made it seem icy. So Uchenna called it out: ‘You don’t care about this, Mom?’ And perhaps it was the incensed way Uchenna had raised her voice, or Iruka’s shock at the accusation, but she had retorted, forcefully: ‘This is eighteen years later. Care now about what happened when?’</p>
<p>And with an uncomfortable silence that stretched, Uchenna listened to her mother: ‘You will do well, young lady, to stop putting me in a box. I am your mother, yet you do not grant me any grace. You are not my remote control. You cannot choose when to keep something a secret, then expect me to rile up at your command because, today you’ve decided to share with your mother what you should’ve shared two decades ago. Why was this hidden from me? Uchenna, I am asking you. Do you not see this as a betrayal? I am your mother.’</p>
<p>‘Then behave like a mother,’ Urenna said later to Iruka as she packed.</p>
<p>‘You are leaving too?’ Iruka asked.</p>
<p>‘Do we have another “perfect” dinner?’ Urenna asked. To this Iruka had nothing to say, but she went to Gozie, who was shaving.</p>
<p>‘Babe?’ Gozie said, sensing his wife’s fury.</p>
<p>‘Don’t Babe me!’</p>
<p>‘What is this about?’</p>
<p>Iruka looked at him, stern, unmoving, her face a mark that offered him nothing. Still, Gozie gave indecipherable explanations until Iruka left and locked herself in her room, only opening it for the staff who took her luggage downstairs.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">–</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>At her second home in Lagos, where she would stay for the next five months, Iruka received countless calls, texts, emails, and letters from Gozie; each laden with promises of a better tomorrow and pleas for forgiveness. Iruka ignored him. It didn’t deter him. He worried her continuously, vowing to stay despite what had happened, promising to be by her side until death parted them if only she would forgive him that one mistake from years ago – the sin that occured then, and which would never happen now or ever again. He wrote: ‘For if God instructed Hosea to marry a harlot, if God forgave David for murder, if Jesus forgave Mary Magdalene, why can’t you become the God of my life and forgive me this betrayal? I would be by your side, be your ride or die. How many men today are willing to be an old gal’s ride or die?’ Iruka ignored him.</p>
<p>‘Who else knew of this?’ Iruka asked Urenna over the phone, weeks later.</p>
<p>‘Just Uche’s therapist.’</p>
<p>‘Uche’s therapist? What do you mean, Uche’s therapist?’</p>
<p>‘Mom –’</p>
<p>‘No, Urenna. Don’t Mom me. At this point, I do not know what to believe.’</p>
<p>‘What do you mean believe? Uchenna was ten.’</p>
<p>‘Yes, she was, but was Uchenna ten five years ago? Was Uchenna ten last year? Is Uchenna ten now? Why now? Why tell her mother now? At sixty-one? Look at me, Urenna –’</p>
<p>‘Mom, what happened to you?’</p>
<p>‘I grew up alone. Should I die alone too? Uchenna hid her academic results from me, and that I forgave. Uchenna hid her first boyfriend from me, and that I forgave. Uchenna hid her life from me, and that too I understood. But now, what is her reason for hiding this from me, and how do I forgive that?’</p>
<p>‘Mom, despite all you say, Uchenna’s stance stands. And she insists she’s always felt shunned by you. So, leave her be. Let her speak when she’s ready. It’s your dear Gozie who sexually harassed your daughter at ten . . .’</p>
<p>‘I’ve heard that many times. I don’t need to hear it again. I’m home alone in this, this big house, am I not?’</p>
<p>‘Mom, please, goodnight. I’m glad you left Gozie. That’s all. I am glad. And I love you. I will check up on you tomorrow, okay?’ Urenna said, ended the call.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">–</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Three days later, Iruka would have a friend over. Seinye, a woman in her late seventies whose husband had died the year before. She would communicate to Iruka in clear terms the dangers of living alone in Nigeria as a woman, especially the dangers of living alone in Nigeria as a wealthy woman. How one’s staff could connive and do the worst.</p>
<p>‘Did you not remember Justice Stella, and how could you forget how her help stabbed her twenty times?’</p>
<p>‘My memory is failing me, you see,’ Iruka said, attributing things to ageing, nearly made a joke about ageing arriving too early, but she restrained herself.</p>
<p>Seinye was still speaking: ‘I am not saying you should return to Gozie. What he did will always be despicable. But you said this happened when?’</p>
<p>‘Almost twenty years ago. Eighteen years.’</p>
<p>‘Well, eighteen is almost twenty, so yes, twenty years ago,’ The woman said. Iruka sighed. There was a brief silence. Iruka wondered if the woman could read her, if the words spoken were merely echoes, if the woman was saying what she assumed Iruka needed to hear.</p>
<p>‘What do they want you to do now? Live alone? Remarry? Travel? Move into an old people’s home? I mean, you definitely cannot spend the rest of your years like this. You have your businesses to run, all those boards, or are you thinking of retirement? You are sixty-one.’</p>
<p>‘Be honest with me, Seinye, please. What would you do in my shoes?’</p>
<p>‘Iruka, my sister. Truly, I would follow my heart.’</p>
<p>‘Which is?’</p>
<p>‘Do what you have to do. You must survive. Let me ask you –’</p>
<p>‘Okay?’</p>
<p>‘When they did not tell you, were you not living with this man?’</p>
<p>‘Well yeah, but . . .’</p>
<p>‘Forget buts. Do what keeps you alive. Maybe start with your imagination, do you understand me? Imagine they did not tell you . . .’ she said. Iruka looked at her.</p>
<p>‘Granted, what Gozie did is grave,’ she said. ‘But forgiveness carries a deeper significance, and as children of God, are we not commanded to give more to those who give less? Forgiveness is the high road. Take it.’</p>
<p>‘Thank you for coming, Seinye. I will send a non-disclosure. Please sign it, but do not mind it.’</p>
<p>More friends would come or call, but with them, Iruka couldn’t share her bother. Calls from Urenna, once frequent, declined with time. So, Iruka turned to her work. She visited Sir Gozie Academy, shared moments with her teachers, returned to her corporations, and tried, if only barely, to focus. But from time to time, she would pine for real conversations, not the filtered memos from her staff. And, spontaneously, she would pick up her phone but repress the urge to call Gozie, whose calls, text, emails, letters kept coming.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">–</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>One evening, in the fourth month of living alone, Iruka slipped while bathing and fell hard onto the bathroom floor, narrowly missing the tub. Lying there, groaning, she reached for a white towel, before stretching, attempting to get to her phone. The more she tried, the harder it became. But she continued, crawling, slowly, steadily.</p>
<p>After Iruka shouted at her chef for leaving the house without her permission, she was shouted at by Seinye. Iruka had called her from the floor.</p>
<p>‘Are you going to kill yourself because of what happened twenty years ago?’ Seinye had said. ‘Time heals, Iruka! Time heals. Or do you think Gozie is still the same man he was twenty years ago?’</p>
<p>When Iruka did nothing but groan, Seinye said, ‘Iruka, you will die alone in that house. Is that what you want?’ Iruka palmed her mouth to muffle her weeping, to keep it from reaching Seinye’s ears.</p>
<p>She ended the call at the exact time her chef rushed in. Iruka had barely managed to cover her nakedness with the white towel.</p>
<p>‘Thank you,’ Iruka said in a soft tone. But this woman – who should’ve closed her eyes after helping Iruka sit up, or quietly left after helping her settle on the couch, asked, ‘Madam, anything else?’ And Iruka’s anger caved her. In Igbo, she slipped into a vibrating tone she rarely used: ‘But what are you still doing here? What more do you want your eyes to see: more shame? Will it fill your belly? How many soups will my shame cook for you?’</p>
<p>Genuflecting, the woman apologized, backing out towards the door at the further end of the living room. Iruka paused, then called after her. ‘Fetch me Dr. Ikemba. No. Fetch Dr. Uzoechi. Uju Uzoechi. Thanks.’</p>
<p>Over the next few weeks, she stayed in bed, thinking of Uchenna as much as she thought of Gozie. The possibility of returning and permanently staying with Gozie never comfortably made sense to her, yet she had the urge to see him – to stare at him one more time, to try and understand what he was thinking eighteen years ago. How could anyone recall what they were thinking eighteen years ago. Time had proven itself an ulcer in this matter. On some level, Iruka had always known that Gozie’s morality would not hold up if observed under stringent measures. Gozie, the city boy with steeze. Hadn’t she crushed on City Boy Gozie because he had, in abundance, that aura?</p>
<p>Yet she had tamed him – or she had assumed. It was, after all, the most essential part of their love story, her taming of him. She had turned him into a small, affable man, eager to please. Adoring his feline eyes was the easiest part. She was no fan of gatherings and parties, and unlike Mark Akintola, Gozie was adept at hosting, adroit at garnishing everyone with compliments that carried a disarming candor. When she courted business associates and investors, he charmed them, softening their doubts until they signed up for Iruka’s bids – his softest skill. For that, Iruka loved him. To be honest (though she had never thought of him in this way until now) he was her dog.</p>
<p>To outsiders, Gozie was in charge. It was the impression Iruka cultivated in interviews, where she repeatedly referred to him as <em>my husband</em>, attributing to him the noble deeds that portrayed her as a taciturn mistress saved by a gallant gentleman. Yet the simple truth was this: he was that familiar twine that made her endure climbing life. And after all these years, she had not merely grown fond of him, but accustomed to him. What ageing body ever separated easily from that to which it is addicted?</p>
<p>After the fall, she called Urenna and called Uchenna. None of them picked up nor returned the calls.</p>
<p>‘An empty stone forms in my heart,’ Iruka texted Urenna.</p>
<p>‘Mom, I understand. I will call soon. My boyfriend is involved in an accident.’</p>
<p>‘Is he okay?’ Iruka texted.</p>
<p>‘Yes, thanks. Brb soon. Love you.’ Urenna texted back. Iruka slept with the phone close to her chest. In the morning, it was the first thing she checked, her phone. Urenna didn’t call. Iruka stewed.</p>
<p>Three days later, Urenna texted. ‘Let’s plan a vacay. The 3 of us. Mom, what do you think?’ It was a group text. Uchenna didn’t reply. Iruka looked at the words and wondered if they had expected her to respond with infantile cheer, to say, ‘Yay.’</p>
<p>‘Yayy,’ she sent to the group text. Nothing came after that.</p>
<p>Thrice, she visited Uchenna’s house, but the gateman said she was not around, though Uchenna’s cars were in the driveway. Iruka cried, and she cried more, for loneliness, which she understood acutely; in its throes, it caged her. And work required the effort she lacked. Like Seinye suggested, she considered paying a man a monthly salary to stay with her, to simply massage her. She tried, but the first man seemed addicted to his phone, and the second man didn’t stop complaining about his mother, as though he had expected Iruka to replace his mother. The third had taken Iruka’s money and never showed up. It made her laugh. In her quest for happiness, the silliest things made her laugh – forced laughter, bereft of hearty cheers. At sixty-one, Iruka was closer to the grave and its grief than to happiness.</p>
<p>The next morning, she forgot herself and walked into empty rooms, calling Gozie’s name. When she realized the mistake minutes later, when she remembered herself, Iruka was flushed with a forlorn sense of shame.</p>
<p>‘My sister, men will stain your white. Up to you to wash the stain and wear it back, or discard the white and buy a new one,’ Seinye said.</p>
<p>‘What does that mean?’ Iruka asked.</p>
<p>‘I am just saying he is a man, a human. A low-tier human, I must add. But at least you know his monstrosities.’</p>
<p>A week later, again Iruka called Urenna and called Uchenna. Neither picked up nor returned her calls.</p>
<p>‘My boyfriend’s mom came to see us. I will call right after,’ Urenna texted the next day. She did call, but towards the end of the conversation, she asked for a cash advance, which Iruka gave her.</p>
<p>That week, on a sunny evening, Iruka called Seinye, who went over that same night with three helpers to assist with her packing.</p>
<p>‘Good Decision’ would be the subject of the email Iruka sent to Urenna and Uchenna. In it, she made it clear that her return to Gozie was impermanent, merely for investigation purposes. ‘Just to be sure, to behold him and hold him up to the light of my anger.’</p>
<p>When she sent it – after she sent it – Iruka wondered what it meant: to hold him up to the light of her anger. It sounded like one of those buzzwords she hated, words that confused rather than convinced. Yet, <em>confusing</em> wasn’t her intention, nor was <em>convincing</em>. Iruka simply wished to live the rest of her life on Earth with a person whose flaws she had seen, whose faults she knew. Though her return to Enugu wasn’t meant to be forever with Gozie – that much Iruka was sure of – she still found herself confused. And what an irony it was. Iruka was a planner, forward-facing, a woman who minded tomorrow. Wasn’t that the very meaning of her name? Iruka – <em>tomorrow will be brighter, tomorrow will be greater</em>. The future is better.</p>
<p>The day before her flight, with her things packed and waiting in the reception room, Iruka had found an email from Urenna. She read it at 6.30 a.m. after her exercise. That was when she usually read emails her PA had assigned to the non-emergency folder. ‘Nothing from family is emergency,’ Iruka had told the PA.</p>
<p>‘Dear Iruka Ndidi Akintola,’ Urenna began the brief email. It left Iruka breathless – not because Urenna questioned her motherhood, or her kindness, or her sense of duty, but because of the email’s certainty, its firmness. The girls were edging toward the line she feared: court, publicity, social media, magazines. Iruka ran her eyes across the last paragraph:</p>
<p>You are not returning to investigate. You are returning to him. What sort of mother lies to herself in such a deplorable way? You are an imitation, not a mother, a facsimile. You say you love him too much. Iruka, all I hear is how deeply you loathe yourself.</p>
<p>That night, Iruka dreamt of Urenna. In her dream, Uchenna’s face was in her hand, a lifelike mask that seemed eerily real. Behind her, plastered on the wall, were more pictures of Uchenna. She woke up as if pulled from a lake. After a moment, she stood and went to her laptop, reread the email and pressed the reply button:</p>
<blockquote><p>Re: Good Decision.</p>
<p>Dear Uchenna,</p>
<p>I will always be with you, but as for now, as you already know, I will be returning to the house in Enugu. Before going on with your own plan, please, wait until you’ve learned that I’ve gone to rest; let waiting be a favour. In short, make it your final favour to me. When you do so, that is when you learn of my departure, feel free, only then, to do whatever you want with my name.</p>
<p>I do not know what I did to you.</p>
<p>Yet, you have, time and again, betrayed me without so much as a moment’s consideration or even clear reflection. Still, I ask my dear. No – Not ask. I beg you my dearest daughter that we please end this malice between us while I am alive. I am tired. Still, I remember you fondly, how, as a child, you never fell asleep without holding my ring finger. I miss that. Not that I’m asking you to be a child; I’m asking you to be my child, to forgive me for buckling under the heft of old age.</p>
<p>Rememeber your mother in the days of your youth, and do not punish her greying days.</p>
<p>Yours,<br />
Iruka</p></blockquote>
<p>Iruka read the email twice. After the third read, she pressed send.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p style="text-align: center;">–</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Erasmus parked in the middle of the drive, turned off the AC, and watched the rest of the convoy as they continued to the parking garage. After a moment of silence, looking through the mirror, he glanced at Iruka and said once, and then twice, ‘Madam?’</p>
<p>‘Erasmus?’ Her tone was gentle, graceful and respectful.</p>
<p>‘We are home, Madam.’</p>
<p>‘We are? You parked?”</p>
<p>‘Yes, Madam.’</p>
<p>She sighed. ‘My God, my memory.’</p>
<p>‘Yes Madam.’</p>
<p>‘My luggage?’</p>
<p>‘Yes Madam. In the second car. Daniel will take it up immediately . . .’</p>
<p>‘I do not like <em>will</em>, Erasmus. Please tell Daniel I asked for my luggage. Thank you.’</p>
<p>Iruka rang the bell for her staff after ensuring her room was clean. To each, she gave a brown envelope. Usually, after long travels, she made it a duty to gift them bottles of luxury perfumes. But because this journey was unusual, because she carried on these days as if her life was no longer hers, she gave them cash instead. They had kept her house well, organized, and stable.</p>
<p>To no one in particular, Iruka said, ‘Please get someone to look at that tennis court. From up at the driveway, it was so dusty. Get it cleaned. Thanks.’</p>
<p>After that brief encounter with her staff, she stayed in her gilt room. Freshened up, left her phones downstairs but never returned, not even after learning that Gozie had arrived.</p>
<p>In the evening, she tiptoed past Gozie’s room as she moved around the house. It smelled as she’d left it, the whole house. She walked through the rooms, opening the doors and standing at the threshold to glance in. When she came to the one between the cinema and the game room, she stood before the door but did not open it, placed her hand on its glistening handle but failed to turn it. A minute later, she moved away, concluding her inspection.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><em>Image <a href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/2.0/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">©</a> Bekky Bekks</em></p>
